<HEADLINE>
The Beatles and Patriotism
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> marcus &lt;marcus...@yahoo.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-07-04T09:59:00 </POSTDATE>
As I usually do on the anniversary of my country's birth, I think
about patriotism...what it means.  For many, patriotism is how one
serves the country.  When I was a child, the only way was to be a
member of the armed forces.

The Beatles changed all that.  They were &quot;foreigners&quot; to those of us
in the US, and yet they were like us.   Their popularity, and
eventually the meaning of many of their songs, ushered in a worldview
perspective for those of us living in the United States.  This
phenomenon was not unique to America as The Beatles became accepted by
people as far apart as Italy, Japan, Australia, and although a bit
more cautiously, in the Soviet Union.

A worldwide citizenry, where people recognized the commonality they
had with others across the globe, and the realization that all people
desired the same things...peace, safety, good health, nourishment, and
love...stripped away the national boundaries.  People were still proud
of the region they lived in, but they realized that the future of the
world was far more important.

So, although I am proud to be a citizen of the United States, despite
the slippery slope slide away from democracy our current crop of
leaders are engaged, I recognize that The Beatles, and the era of good
will they began, is the right direction for loyalty...a loyalty to the
Earth, no matter what language we speak.
</POST>
